Sorry!

This is a visual experience based on colour and movement and so requires CSS.

Even if you can't see the result, here is how it was made.

A HTML preprocessor, Jade/Pug, was used to create the elements. Here is the code:

- var n = 10
// Create overlays
- for (var y = 0; y < n; y++)
    - for (var x = 0; x < n; x++)
        div(id="o_#{ x }_#{ y }" class="overlay")

// Create blocks
- for (var y = 0; y < n; y++)
    - for (var x = 0; x < n; x++)
        div(id="b_#{ x }_#{ y }" class="block")

SCSS, a CSS preprocessor, was used to create the colours and hover effects. Here is the code:

// Variables
$n: 10;
$h: 100% / $n;
$hue: 360 / $n;
$saturation: 50 / $n;

// Position overlays and blocks
@for $y from 0 through $n - 1 {
  @for $x from 0 through $n - 1 {
    
    #o_#{$x}_#{$y},
    #b_#{$x}_#{$y} {
      top: $x * $h;
      left: $y * $h;
      background-color: hsl($hue * $x, 50 + $saturation * $y, 50);
    }
    
  }
}

// Style the hovers
@for $overlayY from 0 through $n - 1 {
  @for $overlayX from 0 through $n - 1 {
    @for $targetY from 0 through $n - 1 {
      @for $targetX from 0 through $n - 1 {
        // Calculate distance from mouse
        $deltaX: $targetX - $overlayX;
        $deltaY: $targetY - $overlayY;
        $a: $deltaX * $deltaX;
        $b: $deltaY * $deltaY;
        $c: $a + $b;
        
        // Don't divide by 0
        @if $c == 0 {
          $c: 1;
        }
        
        // Set the opacity
        #o_#{$overlayX}_#{$overlayY}:hover ~ #b_#{$targetX}_#{$targetY} {
          opacity: 1 / $c;
          transform: translateY(-10 / $deltaX + px) translateX(-10 / $deltaY + px);
        }
        
      }
    }
  }
}
